# Deployment overview

This guide walks through deploying a production instance for your repair cafe. The recommended path uses **MongoDB Atlas** + **Render**, but the same configuration applies to other hosts.

## Architecture recap

You will deploy **three things**:

1. **MongoDB database** (Atlas or self-hosted)
2. **API server** (Node/Express)
3. **Frontend static site** (Expo web build)

```
Users → https://your-cafe.example.org  (frontend static files)
              │
              └── API calls → https://your-api.onrender.com/api
                                    │
                                    └── MongoDB Atlas
```

## Pre-deployment checklist

- [ ] MongoDB Atlas cluster created with a database user and network access configured
- [ ] Strong `JWT_SECRET` generated (32+ random characters)
- [ ] API `.env` values ready (or platform environment variables)
- [ ] Frontend `API_URL` set to your **production** API URL (including `/api` suffix)
- [ ] At least one **admin** user created in MongoDB
- [ ] Custom domain DNS planned (optional)

## Recommended deployment order

| Step | Action | Doc |
|------|--------|-----|
| 1 | Create MongoDB cluster | [MongoDB Atlas](./mongodb-atlas.md) |
| 2 | Deploy API | [Deploy the API](./deploy-api.md) |
| 3 | Verify API health | `curl https://YOUR-API/api/` |
| 4 | Create admin user | [First admin user](../operations/first-admin-user.md) |
| 5 | Build and deploy frontend | [Deploy the frontend](./deploy-frontend.md) |
| 6 | Log in and smoke-test | Create a test event, add a volunteer |

## Environment summary

### API (production)

```env
NODE_ENV=production
PRODUCTION_DATABASE_CONNECTION_STRING=mongodb+srv://...
JWT_SECRET=...
JWT_EXPIRATION=6d
JWT_ISSUER=your-cafe
JWT_AUDIENCE=your-cafe
COST_UNITS=usd
WEIGHT_UNITS=lbs
PORT=3000
```

Render sets `PORT` automatically — do not hard-code a public port.

### Frontend (production build)

```env
API_URL=https://your-api-host.example.com/api
COST_UNITS=usd
WEIGHT_UNITS=lbs
```

Rebuild the frontend whenever `API_URL` changes — it is baked into the bundle at build time.

## Deploy both services on every release

The API and frontend are **separate git submodules** and **separate deployments**. If you fix a bug in the frontend, you must rebuild and redeploy the static site. API-only deploys do not update the web app.

See [Updating a deployment](../operations/updating.md).

## Hosting alternatives

| Approach | API | Frontend | When to use |
|----------|-----|----------|-------------|
| Render (documented) | Web service | Static site | Easiest; free tier |
| Docker | Container on any host | Static nginx or CDN | You already use containers |
| VPS | PM2 + nginx reverse proxy | nginx static root | Full control, one server |

Docker notes: `api/Dockerfile` exists but pins Node 16 — update the base image to Node 22 before production use, or run without Docker using `npm run start:prod`.

## Security notes
- Restrict MongoDB network access to known IPs when possible
- Use HTTPS everywhere (Render provides this by default)
- Never commit `.env` files to git
- Rotate `JWT_SECRET` if compromised (invalidates all sessions)

